SIMPLE: phonography
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phonography
<hw>Pho*nog"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Phono-</ets> + <ets>-graphy</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
description of the laws of the human voice, or sounds uttered by the
organs of speech.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A representation of sounds by distinctive
characters; commonly, a system of shorthand writing invented by
<person>Isaac Pitman</person>, or a modification of his system, much
used by reporters.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ The consonants are represented by straight lines and
curves; the vowels by dots and short dashes; but by skilled
phonographers, in rapid work, most vowel marks are omitted, and brief
symbols for common words and combinations of words are extensively
employed. The following line is an example of phonography, in which all
the sounds are indicated: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- illustr. of phonetic transcription of the line below -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They also serve who only stand and wait.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p></note>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The art of constructing, or using, the
phonograph.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phonolite</ent>⟦br⟧
